                            <h3 class="cs-sign-title">Overgrown Shrubs & Trees</h3>
                            <p class="cs-sign-text">Branches blocking windows, rubbing the house, or crowding walkways are more than ugly. Overgrown desert plants trap heat against walls, hide irrigation leaks, and hold dried material that becomes a fire risk during peak season.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li class="cs-sign">
                            <h3 class="cs-sign-title">Weeds Taking Over</h3>
                            <p class="cs-sign-text">When goathead, tumbleweed, and crabgrass spread faster than you can keep up, it’s time for a different approach. Weed lawn care only works if someone times the pre-emergent to Las Cruces spring and fall surges and follows through with targeted hand removal.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li class="cs-sign">
                            <h3 class="cs-sign-title">Plants Looking Stressed or Half-Dead</h3>
                            <p class="cs-sign-text">Yellow leaves, thin canopies, leggy growth, and sudden shrub death usually come from chlorosis (iron locked up by alkaline soil), poor irrigation, wrong pruning timing, or all three. These are fixable with the right plan and a crew that knows desert plants.</p>
                        </li>
                        <li class="cs-sign">
                            <h3 class="cs-sign-title">Your Last Landscaper Quit</h3>
